supportDesc.extent:
i+i+92+i+i+i and unfoliated inserted paper leaves. Fol. 1r is blank.
225 153 .
supportDesc.foliation: The manuscript is foliated in the top right-hand corners of the recto pages.

condition.p: Two leaves are missing at the end of the codex and there are two lacunae, each taking up one leaf. The first is after fol. 85, the second after fol. 86. Blank pages have been inserted between fols 85 and 86, and fols 86 and 87, and after fol. 92 indicating the loss of text. The bottom margin of fol. 92 is excised.

layout.p: The manuscript is written in one column with 32 lines per page. Contemporary rubrics in red. Chapter numbering and references to the content from c. 1600.

decoNote.p: Pen-flourished initials and plain majuscules occur in varying colours.

additions.p:
Several sixteenth century-marginalia, referring to the content.
The originally blank fol. 1r bears several notes in a fourteenth century-hand: a mik
vel matu sea mik log hmadr sem
laa oc gak bort I fra. The name of the owner once appeared at the beginning of the verse, but it was later rubbed out.
A great number of other marginal notes in the manuscript, some of them (viz. at the bottom of fols 22v, 32v, 40v and 69v) are more or less obliterate.
Danish marginalia on fols 25v-26r refer to a large part of the content.
On fols 1r and 59r 1,5 lines and 1 line, respectively, are written in runes; the runes are more or less rubbed out.
A provenance note in Old Norse and a prayer to the Virgin in Latin both from the fourteenth century occur on fol. 1r. Prayers to the Virgin are found elsewhere.
On fols 48v and 55v-56r partly obscene verses in Latin occur. A few marginal drawings are also found:
In the bottom margins of fols 29v and 35v imaginary coats-of-arms occur.
Drawings of flowers are found on fols 33v and 34r.
Fol. 34r has a picture of a crowned king, holding an axe. Most probably this drawing is meant to represent King Olav
On fol. 63r a funny sketch of an old man with a long beard was drawn.
Fols 51r, 52r and 53r both have man's heads drawn by the same man.
On fols 76v and 84v another man drew man's heads.
In the bottom margin of fol. 83r a crowned lion is found.
On fols 38v, 46v, 66v and 69v have incomplete drawings of animals.

origin.p:
The manuscript was written in Norway or Iceland c. 1300. The manuscript is possibly written in Norway by an Icelander (see Stefán Karlsson 1979
).

provenance.p:
Names of owners occur on fols 34r, 55v and 57r.
Fol. 1r: Jstud opus afgerus fecit the name of the owner is now rubbed out.
Fol. 54v, top margin: Þæssa bok a ældridh.
Fol. 34r, top margin: fra Þoro sendr herra Sigurði logmanni is written.
This note can be compared with a letter on fol. 69v written by Sigurder.
On fol. 57r the name Sigurðr presbyter Guðlaux son appears. The next known owner is Edvard Edvardsen, vice-principal of Bergen, who gave the codex to Árni Magnússon.

acquisition.p:
In his catalogue of Icelandic parchment manuscripts, now known as AM. 435 a 4to, fols 40v-41r, Árni Magnússon wrote the following on the codex: Sverris saga 4to. elegans Codex,
mutilus in calce. Þessa bok
feck eg i Birgvin af Mag. Ed
vard Edvardsyne, Conrectore þar.
Sverris sgu þessa 4to. hefi
eg uppskrifada in fol. med hendi Asgeirs [i.e. AM 79 fol.] og
fer hun med mier til
Danmerkur, nu 1708.
Sr Jon Halldorsson i Hitar
dali, hafdi hana til lns
fra mier 1710. og skrif
adi af henni Copiu firi sig.
